---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="fraiseql - Compiled GraphQL Engine | FraiseQL"
  description="Core FraiseQL engine: compile-time GraphQL execution with deterministic queries, zero N+1 problems, and multi-database support."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>🍓 fraiseql</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Compiled GraphQL Engine</strong> – The core of the FraiseQL
      ecosystem
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>What It Does</h2>
      <p>
        fraiseql is the heart of the FraiseQL ecosystem. It transforms
        database-first schemas into compiled GraphQL execution engines.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Compile-time optimization</strong>: All GraphQL interpretation
          happens at build time
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deterministic execution</strong>: Fixed execution paths, no
          runtime surprises
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Zero N+1 queries</strong>: Database joins computed at compile
          time
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Multi-database support</strong>: PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite,
          SQL Server
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Strong consistency</strong>: CP (Consistency + Partition
          Tolerance) model
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Why It Exists</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional GraphQL resolvers interpret queries at runtime, leading to:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>N+1 query problems</li>
        <li>Unpredictable performance</li>
        <li>Scattered authorization logic</li>
        <li>Difficult to audit and test</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        fraiseql solves this by moving interpretation to compile time, making
        queries predictable, auditable, and fast.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Key Features</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Schema Definition</strong>: Python/TypeScript decorators for
          schema authoring
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Query Compilation</strong>: Rust compiler validates and
          optimizes
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>SQL Generation</strong>: Pre-computed SQL templates for each
          query
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CQRS Pattern</strong>: Views (v_*) for reads, functions (fn_*)
          for writes
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Field-Level Auth</strong>: Compile-time authorization
          metadata
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Complex Nested Queries</strong>: Joins, aggregations, window
          functions
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Performance</h2>
      <p>
        Performance benchmarks compared to traditional GraphQL and REST
        approaches:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Query latency</strong>: 10-50ms (vs 1-5s for traditional
          GraphQL)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Throughput</strong>: 7-10× faster query execution
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Memory efficiency</strong>: O(n) instead of O(n²) for nested
          queries
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Determinism</strong>: Consistent execution time within 5%
          variance
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        See <a href="/verification">Verification</a> for detailed benchmarks and
        methodology.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Language</strong>: Rust (core engine), Python/TypeScript
          (authoring)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Database Drivers</strong>: sqlx (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite),
          tds (SQL Server)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Runtime</strong>: Tokio (async), Hyper (HTTP)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Testing</strong>: cargo-nextest, Playwright
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Integration with Other Tools</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-wire</strong>: Streaming JSON transport (200K×
          memory efficiency)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>confiture</strong>: Database migrations (600× faster builds)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>pg_tviews</strong>: Materialized views (2,083× faster
          refreshes)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-seed</strong>: Test data generation (300× faster)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraisier</strong>: Deployment orchestration (reference
          implementation)
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Quick Start</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Install fraiseql-cli: <code>npm install fraiseql-cli</code></li>
        <li>
          Create schema.json with your GraphQL types and database mappings
        </li>
        <li>
          Compile: <code>fraiseql compile schema.json</code>
        </li>
        <li>
          Run server:
          <code>fraiseql server --schema schema.compiled.json</code>
        </li>
        <li>Query: Send GraphQL queries to localhost:8080/graphql</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>GitHub Repository</h2>
      <p>
        <a href="https://github.com/fraiseql/fraiseql" target="_blank">
          Visit fraiseql on GitHub →
        </a>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>2,400+ tests</li>
        <li>50+ examples</li>
        <li>Complete documentation</li>
        <li>Active development</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Related Tools</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/ecosystem/fraiseql-wire">fraiseql-wire</a> – Streaming transport</li>
        <li><a href="/ecosystem/confiture">confiture</a> – Migrations</li>
        <li><a href="/ecosystem/pg-tviews">pg_tviews</a> – Materialized views</li>
        <li><a href="/ecosystem">← Back to Ecosystem</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <p style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <a href="/">← Back to Home</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
